SIMPLE: gnomon
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gnomon
<hw>Gno"mon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>gnomon</ets>,
Gr. <?/ one that knows, the index of a sundial. See
<er>Gnome</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Dialing)</fld> <def>The style or pin, which by its
shadow, shows the hour of the day. It is usually set parallel to the
earth's axis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A style or column erected
perpendicularly to the horizon, formerly used in astronomocal
observations. Its principal use was to find the altitude of the sun by
measuring the length of its shadow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>The space included between the
boundary lines of two similar parallelograms, the one within the other,
with an angle in common; <as>as, the <ex>gnomon</ex> <it>bcdefg</it> of
the parallelograms <it>ac</it> and <it>af</it></as>. The parallelogram
<it>bf</it> is the complement of the parallelogram
<it>df.</it></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The index of the hour circle of a globe.</def></p>

<p><ent>Gnomonical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Gnomonic</ent>⟦br⟧
